context: In <a0_0><b5_0>1744<b5_0/><a0_0/>, Burke started at Trinity College Dublin, a Protestant establishment, which up until <b6_0>1793<b6_0/>, did not permit <a1_0><b8_0>Catholics<b8_0/><a1_0/> to take degrees. In <a2_0>1747<a2_0/>, he set up a debating society, "Edmund Burke's Club", which, in 1770, merged with <a3_0><b7_0>TCD's Historical Club<b7_0/><a3_0/> to form the College Historical Society; it is the oldest undergraduate society in the world. The minutes of the meetings of Burke's Club remain in the collection of the Historical Society. Burke graduated from Trinity in <a4_0>1748<a4_0/>. Burke's father wanted him to read Law, and with this in mind he went to London in <b9_0>1750<b9_0/>, where he entered the Middle Temple, before soon giving up legal study to travel in Continental Europe. After eschewing the Law, he pursued a livelihood through writing.
